## .NET 8 Migration: `TimedExecutor`

### Key Breaking Changes

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 |
|---|---|
| `Thread.Abort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | **Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException`** — removed entirely |
| `ThreadAbortException` | Never thrown — dead code |

`Thread.Abort()` was removed because it could corrupt process state by unwinding a thread at arbitrary points (mid-lock, mid-write, etc.).

### Migrated Code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must observe the CancellationToken for
    /// timely cancellation — this is by design in .NET 8+.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);

        try
        {
            // Block the caller, just like the original thread.Join(timeout)
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ex) when (ex.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single exceptions to match original behavior
            throw ex.InnerExceptions[0];
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Async-native overload — prefer this in new code.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(
        Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await work(cts.Token).WaitAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

### Usage — Before vs After

```csharp
// ── .NET Framework (old) ──
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => SlowDatabaseCall(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// ── .NET 8 (new) ──
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct => SlowDatabaseCall(ct),   // pass token into the work
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));

// ── .NET 8 async (preferred) ──
var result = await executor.ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync(
    async ct => await SlowDatabaseCallAsync(ct),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(30));
```

### Critical Pitfalls

1. **Cooperative cancellation is not `Abort()`** — If `work` ignores the `CancellationToken`, it will **run to completion** even after the timeout. There is no safe way to forcibly kill work in .NET 8. You must plumb the token into I/O calls (`HttpClient`, `DbCommand`, `Stream.ReadAsync`, etc.).

2. **Third-party code that can't take a token** — As a last resort, you can run it in a separate *process* and kill that, but never rely on `Thread.Abort` equivalents.

3. **`Task.Run` uses the ThreadPool** — The original code created a dedicated thread. If your work is very long-running, use `Task.Factory.StartNew` with `TaskCreationOptions.LongRunning`.

4. **`GetAwaiter().GetResult()` can deadlock** — If called on a UI/ASP.NET sync context. Prefer the async overload in those environments.

5. **Exception semantics changed** — `Task.Run` wraps exceptions in `AggregateException`; the migrated code unwraps single inner exceptions to match the original `throw new AggregateException(error)` behavior.
